        "title": "The portion of the wicked — fire, brimstone, and the cup of divine justice",
        "range": "11:6",
        "excerpt": "Upon the wicked He will rain snares; fire and brimstone and burning wind will be the portion of their cup.",
        "body": "The judicial sentence of verse 6 is one of the most concentrated apocalyptic images in the Psalter. Three instruments of divine judgment are stacked: fire (*esh*), brimstone (*gophrit*), and scorching wind (*zalaphah ruach*). The fire-and-brimstone pairing is the unmistakable fingerprint of Sodom and Gomorrah (Genesis 19:24 — 'the LORD rained upon Sodom and upon Gomorrah fire and brimstone'). Every Israelite reader would hear the echo immediately. The counselors' question of verse 3 — 'if the foundations are destroyed, what can the righteous do?' — finds its answer here in the negative: the wicked cannot do anything when God acts, because the God who rained on Sodom has not changed.\n\nThe 'cup' (*menat*) imagery reinforces the judicial precision of the judgment. The cup in the Psalter and prophets is the vessel of divine apportionment — containing either blessing (Ps. 16:5; 23:5) or judgment (Ps. 75:8; Isaiah 51:17; Jeremiah 25:15; Revelation 14:10). Each person has a portion; the wicked's cup is filled not with refreshment but with the three instruments named. The cup metaphor makes the judgment proportional and personal: this is their measured share, appointed for them, not a cosmic accident.\n\nThe 'rain' (*matar*) verb is the psalm's final irony. The wicked have bent the bow and aimed arrows from darkness (v.2). God's response is to rain — a far more comprehensive projectile pattern — on them. Their covert assault becomes God's overt judicial volley. Peter Davids (*The First Epistle of Peter*, NIGTC) noting similar judgment-reversal patterns in the New Testament observes that the eschatological reversal of Psalm 11 is exactly the logic Paul employs in 2 Thessalonians 1:6-8: God is just; He will repay with affliction those who afflict His people.\n\nThe tense is future but certain: the bows are still bent at the moment of the psalm's writing. Faith holds the not-yet judgment as a present anchor — the rain has not fallen, but the cloud is forming over the head of the one who loves violence."
